|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Hong Kong|Law}}\n* [[Legal system of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Supreme Court of Hong Kong]]\n*[[Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal]]\n*[[High Court (Hong Kong)]]\n*[[Chief Judge of the High Court of Hong Kong]]\n*[[Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List (Hong Kong)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.hkcfa.hk/en/home/index.html Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal]\n* [http://www.judiciary.gov.hk/en/crt_services/pphlt/html/cfa.htm Hong Kong Judiciary website page on Court of Final Appeal]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040908084642/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/world/hongkong.htm Jurist Hong Kong]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Judiciary of Hong Kong}}\n{{Asia topic | Supreme Court of |title = Supreme Courts of Asia }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Court Of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)}}\n[[Category:Judiciary of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)| ]]\n[[Category:Subnational supreme courts|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Government Hill]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "CityPride", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFormer Non-Permanent Judges from Other Common Law Jurisdictions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Court_of_Final_Appeal_(Hong_Kong)"}
{"title_page": "The Life of Fish", "text_new": "{{short description|2010 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Life of Fish\n| image          = The Life of Fish.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Mat\u00edas Bize]]\n| producer       = [[Adri\u00e1n Solar]]\n| writer         = [[Mat\u00edas Bize]]<br>[[Julio Rojas]]\n| starring       = [[Santiago Cabrera]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = B\u00e1rbara \u00c1lvarez\n| editing        = Javier Est\u00e9vez\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2010|6|10}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes\n| country        = Chile\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''The Life of Fish''''' ({{lang-es|'''La vida de los peces'''}}) is a 2010 Chilean [[drama film]] directed by [[Mat\u00edas Bize]]. The film was selected as the Chilean entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[83rd Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"lanacion.cl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.cl/-la-vida-de-los-peces-postulara-a-ternas-de-mejor-pelicula-extranjera-en-los-oscar/noticias/2010-10-01/173144.html |title=\"La vida de los peces\" postular\u00e1 a ternas de Mejor Pel\u00edcula Extranjera en los Oscar |accessdate=2 October 2010 |work=lanacion.cl |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006004549/http://lanacion.cl/-la-vida-de-los-peces-postulara-a-ternas-de-mejor-pelicula-extranjera-en-los-oscar/noticias/2010-10-01/173144.html |archivedate=6 October 2010  }}</ref> but didn't make the final shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar Shortlist\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2011/20110119.html |title=9 Foreign Language Films Continue to Oscar Race |accessdate=19 January 2011|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n\n''The Life of Fish'' won the award for [[Goya Award for Best Spanish Language Foreign Film|Best Spanish Language Foreign Film]] at the [[25th Goya Awards]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Santiago Cabrera]] as Andr\u00e9s\n* [[Blanca Lewin]] as Beatriz\n* [[Antonia Zegers]] as Mariana\n* [[V\u00edctor Montero]] as Pablo\n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n Layseca]] as Ignacio\n* [[Juan Pablo Miranda]] as Roberto\n* Luz Jim\u00e9nez as Guille\n* [[Mar\u00eda Gracia Omegna]] as Carolina\n* [[Alicia Rodr\u00edguez (Chilean actress)|Alicia Rodr\u00edguez]] as Daniela\n* [[Francisca C\u00e1rdenas]] as Maca\n* [[Diego Fontecilla]] as Jorge\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 83rd Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Chilean submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|1672078|The Life of Fish}}\n\n{{Chilean submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life Of Fish}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:Chilean films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:2010 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chilean drama films]]\n{{Chile-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2010 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Life of Fish\n| image          = The Life of Fish.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Mat\u00edas Bize]]\n| producer       = [[Adri\u00e1n Solar]]\n| writer         = [[Mat\u00edas Bize]]<br>[[Julio Rojas]]\n| starring       = [[Santiago Cabrera]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = B\u00e1rbara \u00c1lvarez\n| editing        = Javier Est\u00e9vez\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2010|6|10}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes\n| country        = Chile\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''The Life of Fish''''' ({{lang-es|'''La vida de los peces'''}}) is a 2010 Chilean [[drama film]] directed by [[Mat\u00edas Bize]]. The film was selected as the Chilean entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[83rd Academy Awards]],<ref name=\"lanacion.cl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.cl/-la-vida-de-los-peces-postulara-a-ternas-de-mejor-pelicula-extranjera-en-los-oscar/noticias/2010-10-01/173144.html |title=\"La vida de los peces\" postular\u00e1 a ternas de Mejor Pel\u00edcula Extranjera en los Oscar |accessdate=2 October 2010 |work=lanacion.cl |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006004549/http://lanacion.cl/-la-vida-de-los-peces-postulara-a-ternas-de-mejor-pelicula-extranjera-en-los-oscar/noticias/2010-10-01/173144.html |archivedate=6 October 2010  }}</ref> but didn't make the final shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar Shortlist\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2011/20110119.html |title=9 Foreign Language Films Continue to Oscar Race |accessdate=19 January 2011|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n\n''The Life of Fish'' won the award for [[Goya Award for Best Spanish Language Foreign Film|Best Spanish Language Foreign Film]] at the [[25th Goya Awards]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Santiago Cabrera]] as Andr\u00e9s\n* [[Blanca Lewin]] as Beatriz\n* [[Antonia Zegers]] as Mariana\n* [[V\u00edctor Montero]] as Pablo\n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n Layseca]] as Ignacio\n* [[Juan Pablo Miranda]] as Roberto\n* Luz Jim\u00e9nez as Guille\n* [[Mar\u00eda Gracia Omegna]] as Carolina\n* [[Alicia Rodr\u00edguez (Chilean actress)|Alicia Rodr\u00edguez]] as Daniela\n* [[Francisca C\u00e1rdenas]] as Maca\n* [[Diego Fontecilla]] as Jorge\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 83rd Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Chilean submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|1672078|The Life of Fish}}\n\n{{Chilean submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life Of Fish}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:Chilean films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:2010 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chilean drama films]]\n{{Chile-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Life_of_Fish"}
{"title_page": "Rinko Kawauchi", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rinko Kawauchi<br>[[Royal_Photographic_Society#Distinctions_and_qualifications|HonFRPS]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1972|04|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shiga]], [[Japan]]\n| nationality        = Japenese\n| education          = Seian University of Art and Design\n| occupation         = Photographer\n}}\n'''Rinko Kawauchi''' [[Royal_Photographic_Society#Distinctions_and_qualifications|HonFRPS]] (\u5ddd\u5185 \u502b\u5b50, ''Kawauchi Rinko,'' born 1972) is a Japanese [[photographer]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shearer|first1=Benjamin F.|last2=Shearer|first2=Barbara Smith|title=Notable women in the life sciences : a biographical dictionary|date=1996|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn. [u.a.]|isbn=0313293023|pages=440|edition=1. publ.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bjp-online.com/public/showPage.html?page=857752 |title= Celebrated Japanese photographers come to London |date= 2009-05-12|accessdate=2010-02-01|publisher=[[British Journal of Photography]]}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.public-image.org/interview/2008/04/22/rinko-kawauchi.html|title=Interview: RINKO KAWAUCHI - \u5ddd\u5185\u502b\u5b50 - Photographer|date=2008-04-22|accessdate=2010-02-01|publisher=www.public-image.org]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108105440/http://www.public-image.org/interview/2008/04/22/rinko-kawauchi.html|archivedate=2009-01-08}}</ref> Her work is characterized by a serene, poetic style, depicting the ordinary moments in life.<ref>{{cite news |title= Joyless, creepy - and sublime|first= Alastair \n|last= Sooke |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]]|date= 2006-06-06 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/3652948/Joyless-creepy---and-sublime.html|quote=Her intimate imagery is worlds apart from that of her co-exhibitors: a newborn with umbilical cord still attached; a green shoot sprouting from a bulb; and, most startling, a cracked egg containing a fluffy hatchling. You come away from her gentle show refreshed.}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title= Sublime to meticulousJapan's young master finds magic in bugs, clouds and trees |first= Sean | last= O'Hagan  |newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date= 2006-05-07 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2006/may/07/art1|quote=Rinko Kawauchi's subject is the everyday sublime}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nKawauchi became interested in photography while studying graphic design and photography at [[Seian University of Art and Design]] where she graduated in 1993.<ref name=\"heine-finger\">Florian Heine & Brad Finger. Rinko Kawauchi. ''50 Contemporary Photographers You Should Know''. Munich: Prestel 2016.</ref> She first worked in commercial photography<ref name=\"heine-finger\"/> for an advertising agency for several years before embarking on a career as a fine art photographer. She has mentioned that she continues to work the advertising job.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Risch|first=Conor|url=https://go-gale-com.proxy-remote.galib.uga.edu/ps/i.do?p=ITOF&u=uga&id=GALE&#124;A274786499&v=2.1&it=r&sid=ebsco|title=In a moment: with her first collaboration with a U.S. publisher, renowned Japanese photographer Rinko Kawauchi shares her take on our collective experience|date=2011|work=Photo District News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Her background and experience with design has influenced the edits and arrangements of photos her series. Kawauchi often thinks about new ways to see her photographs, allowing her to continue to find new meaning and significance in her work.<ref name=\":1\" /> There is little known about her personal life and family, but through her photo book \"Cui Cui\" she portrays the memories of her family, which she has said to have been shooting for over a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rinkokawauchi.com/en/publications/382/|title=Cui Cui|last=|first=|date=|website=Rinko Kawauchi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The photos in said book captures all the ordinaries and emotions of life, ranging from the happiness of childbirth to the heartbreak of death. \n\nAt age 19, she began making prints of her first black-and-white photographs, and it wasn't until five years later that she started printing color photographs.<ref name=\":1\" /> After experimenting with different cameras, she decided to stay with the [[Rolleiflex]], which she still uses. \n\nIn 2001, three of her photo books were published: Hanako (a Japanese girl's name), Utatane (\"catnap\"), and Hanabi (\"fireworks\"). In the following years she won prizes for two of the books in Japan.<ref name=\"Friedewald\">Boris Friedewald. ''Women Photographers: From Julia Margaret Cameron to Cindy Sherman''. Munich - London - New York 2014, S. 108, {{ISBN|978-3-7913-4814-8}}</ref> In 2004 Kawauchi published ''Aila''; in 2010, ''Murmuration'', and in 2011 ''Illuminance.''\n\nKawauchi's art is rooted in [[Shinto]], the [[ethnic religion]] of the people of Japan.<ref name=\"Friedewald\">Boris Friedewald. ''Women Photographers: From Julia Margaret Cameron to Cindy Sherman''. Munich - London - New York 2014, S. 108, {{ISBN|978-3-7913-4814-8}}</ref> According to Shinto, all things on earth have a spirit, hence no subject is too small or mundane for Kawauchi's work; she also photographs \"small events glimpsed in passing,\"<ref>Ian Jeffrey. Rinko Kawauchi: ''Murmuration.''Photoworks, 15(Autumn-Winter, 2010), 26-35 https://photoworks.org.uk/project-news/photoworks-issue-15/</ref> conveying a sense of the transient. Kawauchi sees her images as parts of series that allow the viewer to juxtapose images in the imagination, thereby making the photograph a work of art<ref>Yumi Goto, \"[http://time.com/3776240/rinko-kawauchis-illuminance/ Rinko Kawauchi's Illuminance]\". Time, April 11, 2011.</ref> and allowing a whole to emerge at the end; she likes working in photo books because they allow the viewer to engage intimately with her images.<ref name=\"heine-finger\" /> Her photographs are mostly in 6&times;6 format.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://pingmag.jp/2006/08/11/10-questions-to-rinko-kawauchi-about-photography/|title= 10 questions to Rinko Kawauchi about photography  |date=2006-08-11|accessdate=2011-05-12|publisher=pingmag.jp}}</ref> However, upon being invited to the Brighton Photo Biennial in 2010, Kawauchi first photographed digitally and began taking photos that were not square.<ref name=\"heine-finger\" /> \n\nKawauchi also composes [[haiku]] poems. She currently lives and works in [[Tokyo]].\n\n== Style ==\nSince she began her photographic career, Kawauchi's photographs contained a unique aesthetic and mood, capturing intimate, poetic, and beautiful moments of the world around her. They often have brilliant and radiant light that give them a dream-like quality. The sublimity of her photographs are further enhanced by her use of soft colors as well as her awareness for the beauty in even the most average moments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'Hagan|first=Sean|url=https://go-gale-com.proxy-remote.galib.uga.edu/ps/i.do?p=STND&u=uga&id=GALE%7CA501280003&v=2.1&it=r&sid=ebsco|title=Halo by Rinko Kawauchi -- images of the everyday sublime; A book celebrating the earth, the heavens and all points between confirms Kawauchi's standing as a singular presence in modern photography|date=2017-08-21|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere is not one specific theme or concept that Kawauchi chooses to explore with her image creation; rather, she does it spontaneously, observing and reacting to everything that is around her before doing and sort of editing.<ref name=\":1\" /> She focuses on just shooting, photographing everything that attracts her eyes before looking back and thinking about why she was interesting in those subjects. Another subject that she explored in her book, ''Ametsuchi'', was the practice of religious ceremonies and rituals that hinted at an earthly cycle involving the concepts of time and impermanence. In the book, she depicts Japan's [[Mount Aso]], a sacred site for a Shinto ritual called yakihata, and its volcanic landscape.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Kawauchi|first=Rinko|url=https://go-gale-com.proxy-remote.galib.uga.edu/ps/i.do?p=GIC&u=uga&id=GALE&#124;A331969566&v=2.1&it=r&sid=ebsco|title=FIELDS OF FIRE; For her latest project the Japanese photographer Rinko Kawauchi observed the 1,300-year-old tradition of burning farmland, an idea that came to her in a dream|date=2020-06-01|work=Daily Telegraph|access-date=2020-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The ritual is a long-standing tradition dating back about 1,300 years in which farmland is burned yearly to maintain its sustainability for new crops as opposed to using chemicals, and the communities at Aso are among the few that continue this tradition. Ironically, witnessing essentially the rebirth of farmland take place, Kawauchi claims that she burned away her old self and was reborn herself.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn her book ''Halo'', she continues to explore that theme with different rituals at other locations. She traveled to [[Izumo, Shimane|Izumo]], Japan to witness a ritual that involves the lighting of sacred flames to welcome the gods.<ref name=\":0\" /> She also went to the [[Hebei]] province of [[China]] to see new year celebrations, including a 500 year old tradition of throwing molten iron at the city walls to make their own fireworks. \n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2002 [[Kimura Ihei Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gallery916.com/exhibition/therainofblessing/|title=The rain of blessing|last=|first=|date=|website=Gallery 916|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n* 2009 Infinity Award for Art from the [[International Center of Photography]]<ref name=\"heine-finger\" /> \n* 2012 Honorary Fellowship of the [[Royal Photographic Society]]<ref name=\"rps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rps.org/about/awards/history-and-recipients/honorary-fellowships|title=Honorary Fellowships (HonFRPS)|publisher=[[Royal Photographic Society]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127135803/http://www.rps.org/about/awards/history-and-recipients/honorary-fellowships|archive-date=27 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> \n* 2013 Minister of Education Award for New Artists\n* 2013 Higashikawa Domestic Photographer Award\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Hanako.'' 2002.\n* ''Utatane.'' 2002.\n* ''Hanabi'' ({{Nihongo2|\u82b1\u706b}}, Fireworks). Tokyo: Little More, 2002. {{ISBN|4-89815-053-5}}.\n* ''Aila.'' 2004.\n* ''The eyes, the ears.'' 2005.\n* ''Cui Cui.'' 2005.\n* ''Semear.'' 2007.\n* ''Murmuration.'' Brighton: [[Photoworks]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-1-903796-41-2}}.\n* ''One Day - 10 Photographers,'' Heidelberg/Berlin: Kehrer, 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-86828-173-6}}, edited by Harvey Benge.<ref group=\"n\">The publisher's description of this set: {{Cite web|url=https://www.kehrerverlag.com/en/one-day-10-photographers-978-3-86828-173-6|title=One Day - Kehrer Verlag|website=Kehrer Verlag|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n* ''Illuminance.'' New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2011. {{ISBN|978-1597111447}}.\n* ''Approaching Whiteness.'' Tokyo: Goliga, 2012.\n* ''Ametsuchi.'' New York: Aperture, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1597112161}}.\n* ''Light and Shadow''. Kanagawa, Japan : Super Labo,  2014<ref>{{Cite book|title=Light and shadow|last=Kawauchi|first=Rinko|date=2014|isbn=9784905052678|oclc = 907485744}}</ref>\n* ''Halo.'' New York: Aperture, 2017. {{ISBN|1597114111}}.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n=== Solo exhibitions ===\n*1998: ''Utatane'', Guardian Garden, Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapispress.com/rinkokawauchi_detail.htm|title=The Lapis Press|website=www.lapispress.com}}</ref>\n*2006: ''Rinko Kawauchi,'' [[The Photographers' Gallery]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonEvents/RinkoKawauchi/c1b89|title=London Town|publisher=}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.photonet.org.uk/index.php?id=130,578,0,0,1,0 Rinko Kawauchi, 5 May - 9 July 2006, The Photographers' Gallery]\"</ref>\n*2007: ''Semear,'' [[Museu de Arte Moderna de S\u00e3o Paulo]], S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>Rinko Kawauchi, Museu de Arte Moderna de S\u00e3o Paulo, S\u00e3o Paulo 20 jul-23 set 2007 {{cite web |url=http://www.mam.org.br/2008/portugues/exposicaoDetalhes.aspx?id=31 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007230855/http://www.mam.org.br/2008/portugues/exposicaoDetalhes.aspx?id=31 |archivedate=2010-10-07 }}</ref>\n*2010: [[Brighton Museum & Art Gallery]], during [[Brighton Photo Biennial]], ''New Documents,'' curated by [[Martin Parr]], Brighton, UK.<ref>Strange & Familiar: Three Views of Brighton, Brighton Photo Biennial 2010, Oct 2nd - Nov 14th 2010 {{cite web |url=http://www.bpb.org.uk/exhibitions/9148/bpb-curated-strange-familiar-three-views-of-brighton/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517233452/http://bpb.org.uk/exhibitions/9148/bpb-curated-strange-familiar-three-views-of-brighton/ |archivedate=2011-05-17 }}</ref>\n*2011: ''Illuminance,'' Foil Gallery, Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://christopheguye.com/exhibitions/illuminance/introduction|title=Illuminance|publisher=}}</ref>\n*2012: ''Light and Shadow'', Traumaris Photography Space, Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://traumaris.tumblr.com/|title=TRAUMARIS - SPACE - Photo Gallery|website=traumaris.tumblr.com}}</ref>\n*2012: ''Illuminance, Ametsuchi, Seeing Shadow'', [[Tokyo Metropolitan Museum of Photography]], Tokyo.\n*2013: ''Illuminance,'' Christophe Guye Galerie, Zurich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://christopheguye.com/artists/rinko-kawauchi/exhibitions|title=Rinko Kawauchi|publisher=}}</ref>\n*2013: ''Ametsuchi,'' [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture Gallery]], New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aperture.org/traveling-exhibitions/rinko-kawauchi-ametsuchi/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427064742/http://www.aperture.org/traveling-exhibitions/rinko-kawauchi-ametsuchi/ |archivedate=2015-04-27 }}</ref>\n*2014: ''Ametsuchi,'' Galerie Priska Pasquer, Cologne.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://priskapasquer.com/rinko-kawauchi-ametsuchi-december-6-2013-march-8-2014/|title=RINKO KAWAUCHI, Ametsuchi \u2013 PRISKA PASQUER|date=6 December 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n*2014: ''New Pictures 9: Rinko Kawauchi,'' [[Minneapolis Institute of Arts]], Minneapolis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.art-report.com/de/institution/The_Minneapolis_Institute_of_Arts_(MIA)/924|title=The Minneapolis Institute of Arts (MIA) on art-report - de|date=8 December 2015|website=www.art-report.com}}</ref>\n*2014: ''Ametsuchi'', Main Gallery, [[Lesley University|Lesley University College of Art and Design]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lesley.edu/college-art-and-design/events/|title=College of Art & Design - Lesley University|website=www.lesley.edu}}</ref>\u3000\n*2014: ''Light and Shadow'', Colissimo, Hyogo.<ref>[http://colissimo.jp/rizmevent/5630.htm]{{dead link|date=March 2018}}</ref>\n*2015: ''Illuminance,'' [[KunstHausWien]], Vienna, 20 March \u2013 5 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kunsthauswien.com/en/exhibitions/current|title=Home Page \u2013 Kunst Haus Wien. Museum Hundertwasser|website=www.kunsthauswien.com}}</ref>\n*2017: ''Halo,'' Christophe Guye Galerie, Zurich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://christopheguye.com/exhibitions/halo/introduction|title=Halo|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n*2005: ''Autumn 2005'', [[Huis Marseille, Museum for Photography]], [[Netherlands]], 10 September \u2013 4 December 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://huismarseille.nl/en/exhibitions/autumn-2005/|title=Autumn 2005|last=|first=|date=|website=Huis Marseille|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n*2008: ''Creatures from the Collection and Other Themes'', Huis Marseille, Museum for Photography, Netherlands, 31 May \u2013 31 August 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://huismarseille.nl/en/exhibitions/creatures-from-the-collection-and-other-themes/|title=Creatures from the Collection and Other Themes|last=|first=|date=|website=Huis Marseille|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n*2010: ''Summer Loves'', Huis Marselle, Museum for Photography, Netherlands, 5 June \u2013 29 August 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://huismarseille.nl/en/exhibitions/summer-loves/|title=Summer Loves|last=|first=|date=|website=Huis Marseille|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n*2011: ''Bye Bye Kitty!!! Between Heaven and Hell in Contemporary Japanese Art,'' curated by David Elliott, [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]], New York. With Kawauchi and [[Makoto Aida]] (\u4f1a\u7530\u8aa0), Manabu Ikeda (\u6c60\u7530\u5b66), [[Tomoko Kashiki]] (\u6a2b\u6728\u77e5\u5b50), Haruka Kojin (\u8352\u795e\u660e\u9999), Kumi Machida (\u753a\u7530\u4e45\u7f8e), [[Yoshitomo Nara]] (\u5948\u826f\u7f8e\u667a), Kohei Nawa (\u540d\u548c\u6643\u5e73), Motohiko Odani (\u5c0f\u8c37\u5143\u5f66), Hiraki Sawa (\u3055\u308f\u3072\u3089\u304d), [[Chiharu Shiota]] (\u5869\u7530\u5343\u6625), Tomoko Shioyasu (\u5869\u4fdd\u670b\u5b50), [[Tenmyouya Hisashi|Hisashi Tenmyouya]] (\u5929\u660e\u5c4b\u5c1a), Yamaguchi Akira (\u5c71\u53e3\u6643), [[Miwa Yanagi]] (\u3084\u306a\u304e\u307f\u308f) and Tomoko Yoneda (\u7c73\u7530\u77e5\u5b50).\n*2015: ''In the Wake: Japanese Photographers Respond to 3/11,'' [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], MA, 5 April \u2013 12 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.org/exhibitions/in-the-wake|title=In the Wake|date=21 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n*2018: ''A Beautiful Moment,'' Huis Marseille, Museum for Photography, Netherlands, 9 June \u2013 2 September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://huismarseille.nl/en/exhibitions/a-beautiful-moment-collection-japan/|title=A Beautiful Moment|last=|first=|date=|website=Huis Marseille|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\nKawauchi's work is held in the following collections:\n\n* [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]], San Francisco: 7 works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfmoma.org/artist/Rinko_Kawauchi/|title=Rinko Kawauchi|last=|first=|date=|website=sfmoma|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n* Huis Marseilles, Museum for Photography, Amsterdam<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://huismarseille.nl/en/search/rinko+kawauchi/|title=Results for rinko kawauchi|last=|first=|date=|website=Huis Marseille|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n* Tokyo Metropolitan Museum of Photography, Tokyo\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Lieko Shiga]], one of Kawauchi's contemporaries\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.rinkokawauchi.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kawauchi Rinko}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese photographers]]\n[[Category:Japanese women photographers]]\n[[Category:Fine art photographers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Photographic Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rinko Kawauchi<br>[[Royal_Photographic_Society#Distinctions_and_qualifications|HonFRPS]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1972|04|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shiga]], [[Japan]]\n| nationality        = Japenese\n| education          = Seian University of Art and Design\n| occupation         = Photographer\n}}\n'''Rinko Kawauchi''' [[Royal_Photographic_Society#Distinctions_and_qualifications|HonFRPS]] (\u5ddd\u5185 \u502b\u5b50, ''Kawauchi Rinko,'' born 1972) is a [[Japan]]ese [[photographer]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shearer|first1=Benjamin F.|last2=Shearer|first2=Barbara Smith|title=Notable women in the life sciences : a biographical dictionary|date=1996|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn. [u.a.]|isbn=0313293023|pages=440|edition=1. publ.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bjp-online.com/public/showPage.html?page=857752 |title= Celebrated Japanese photographers come to London |date= 2009-05-12|accessdate=2010-02-01|publisher=[[British Journal of Photography]]}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.public-image.org/interview/2008/04/22/rinko-kawauchi.html|title=Interview: RINKO KAWAUCHI - \u5ddd\u5185\u502b\u5b50 - Photographer|date=2008-04-22|accessdate=2010-02-01|publisher=www.public-image.org]|language=Japanese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108105440/http://www.public-image.org/interview/2008/04/22/rinko-kawauchi.html|archivedate=2009-01-08}}</ref> Her work is characterized by a serene, poetic style, depicting the ordinary moments in life.<ref>{{cite news |title= Joyless, creepy - and sublime|first= Alastair \n|last= Sooke |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]]|date= 2006-06-06 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/3652948/Joyless-creepy---and-sublime.html|quote=Her intimate imagery is worlds apart from that of her co-exhibitors: a newborn with umbilical cord still attached; a green shoot sprouting from a bulb; and, most startling, a cracked egg containing a fluffy hatchling. You come away from her gentle show refreshed.}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title= Sublime to meticulousJapan's young master finds magic in bugs, clouds and trees |first= Sean | last= O'Hagan  |newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date= 2006-05-07 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2006/may/07/art1|quote=Rinko Kawauchi's subject is the everyday sublime}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nKawauchi became interested in photography while studying graphic design and photography at [[Seian University of Art and Design]] where she graduated in 1993.<ref name=\"heine-finger\">Florian Heine & Brad Finger. Rinko Kawauchi. ''50 Contemporary Photographers You Should Know''. Munich: Prestel 2016.</ref> She first worked in commercial photography<ref name=\"heine-finger\"/> for an advertising agency for several years before embarking on a career as a fine art photographer. She has mentioned that she continues to work the advertising job.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Risch|first=Conor|url=https://go-gale-com.proxy-remote.galib.uga.edu/ps/i.do?p=ITOF&u=uga&id=GALE&#124;A274786499&v=2.1&it=r&sid=ebsco|title=In a moment: with her first collaboration with a U.S. publisher, renowned Japanese photographer Rinko Kawauchi shares her take on our collective experience|date=2011|work=Photo District News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Her background and experience with design has influenced the edits and arrangements of photos her series. Kawauchi often thinks about new ways to see her photographs, allowing her to continue to find new meaning and significance in her work.<ref name=\":1\" /> There is little known about her personal life and family, but through her photo book \"Cui Cui\" she portrays the memories of her family, which she has said to have been shooting for over a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rinkokawauchi.com/en/publications/382/|title=Cui Cui|last=|first=|date=|website=Rinko Kawauchi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The photos in said book captures all the ordinaries and emotions of life, ranging from the happiness of childbirth to the heartbreak of death. \n\nAt age 19, she began making prints of her first black-and-white photographs, and it wasn't until five years later that she started printing color photographs.<ref name=\":1\" /> After experimenting with different cameras, she decided to stay with the [[Rolleiflex]], which she still uses. \n\nIn 2001, three of her photo books were published: Hanako (a Japanese girl's name), Utatane (\"catnap\"), and Hanabi (\"fireworks\"). In the following years she won prizes for two of the books in Japan.<ref name=\"Friedewald\">Boris Friedewald. ''Women Photographers: From Julia Margaret Cameron to Cindy Sherman''. Munich - London - New York 2014, S. 108, {{ISBN|978-3-7913-4814-8}}</ref> In 2004 Kawauchi published ''Aila''; in 2010, ''Murmuration'', and in 2011 ''Illuminance.''\n\nKawauchi's art is rooted in [[Shinto]], the [[ethnic religion]] of the people of Japan.<ref name=\"Friedewald\">Boris Friedewald. ''Women Photographers: From Julia Margaret Cameron to Cindy Sherman''. Munich - London - New York 2014, S. 108, {{ISBN|978-3-7913-4814-8}}</ref> According to Shinto, all things on earth have a spirit, hence no subject is too small or mundane for Kawauchi's work; she also photographs \"small events glimpsed in passing,\"<ref>Ian Jeffrey. Rinko Kawauchi: ''Murmuration.''Photoworks, 15(Autumn-Winter, 2010), 26-35 https://photoworks.org.uk/project-news/photoworks-issue-15/</ref> conveying a sense of the transient. Kawauchi sees her images as parts of series that allow the viewer to juxtapose images in the imagination, thereby making the photograph a work of art<ref>Yumi Goto, \"[http://time.com/3776240/rinko-kawauchis-illuminance/ Rinko Kawauchi's Illuminance]\". Time, April 11, 2011.</ref> and allowing a whole to emerge at the end; she likes working in photo books because they allow the viewer to engage intimately with her images.<ref name=\"heine-finger\" /> Her photographs are mostly in 6&times;6 format.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://pingmag.jp/2006/08/11/10-questions-to-rinko-kawauchi-about-photography/|title= 10 questions to Rinko Kawauchi about photography  |date=2006-08-11|accessdate=2011-05-12|publisher=pingmag.jp}}</ref> However, upon being invited to the Brighton Photo Biennial in 2010, Kawauchi first photographed digitally and began taking photos that were not square.<ref name=\"heine-finger\" /> \n\nKawauchi also composes [[haiku]] poems. She currently lives and works in [[Tokyo]].\n\n== Style ==\nSince she began her photographic career, Kawauchi's photographs contained a unique aesthetic and mood, capturing intimate, poetic, and beautiful moments of the world around her. They often have brilliant and radiant light that give them a dream-like quality. The sublimity of her photographs are further enhanced by her use of soft colors as well as her awareness for the beauty in even the most average moments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'Hagan|first=Sean|url=https://go-gale-com.proxy-remote.galib.uga.edu/ps/i.do?p=STND&u=uga&id=GALE%7CA501280003&v=2.1&it=r&sid=ebsco|title=Halo by Rinko Kawauchi -- images of the everyday sublime; A book celebrating the earth, the heavens and all points between confirms Kawauchi's standing as a singular presence in modern photography|date=2017-08-21|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere is not one specific theme or concept that Kawauchi chooses to explore with her image creation; rather, she does it spontaneously, observing and reacting to everything that is around her before doing and sort of editing.<ref name=\":1\" /> She focuses on just shooting, photographing everything that attracts her eyes before looking back and thinking about why she was interesting in those subjects. Another subject that she explored in her book, ''Ametsuchi'', was the practice of religious ceremonies and rituals that hinted at an earthly cycle involving the concepts of time and impermanence. In the book, she depicts Japan's [[Mount Aso]], a sacred site for a Shinto ritual called yakihata, and its volcanic landscape.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Kawauchi|first=Rinko|url=https://go-gale-com.proxy-remote.galib.uga.edu/ps/i.do?p=GIC&u=uga&id=GALE&#124;A331969566&v=2.1&it=r&sid=ebsco|title=FIELDS OF FIRE; For her latest project the Japanese photographer Rinko Kawauchi observed the 1,300-year-old tradition of burning farmland, an idea that came to her in a dream|date=2020-06-01|work=Daily Telegraph|access-date=2020-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The ritual is a long-standing tradition dating back about 1,300 years in which farmland is burned yearly to maintain its sustainability for new crops as opposed to using chemicals, and the communities at Aso are among the few that continue this tradition. Ironically, witnessing essentially the rebirth of farmland take place, Kawauchi claims that she burned away her old self and was reborn herself.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn her book ''Halo'', she continues to explore that theme with different rituals at other locations. She traveled to [[Izumo, Shimane|Izumo]], Japan to witness a ritual that involves the lighting of sacred flames to welcome the gods.<ref name=\":0\" /> She also went to the [[Hebei]] province of [[China]] to see new year celebrations, including a 500 year old tradition of throwing molten iron at the city walls to make their own fireworks. \n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2002 [[Kimura Ihei Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gallery916.com/exhibition/therainofblessing/|title=The rain of blessing|last=|first=|date=|website=Gallery 916|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n* 2009 Infinity Award for Art from the [[International Center of Photography]]<ref name=\"heine-finger\" /> \n* 2012 Honorary Fellowship of the [[Royal Photographic Society]]<ref name=\"rps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rps.org/about/awards/history-and-recipients/honorary-fellowships|title=Honorary Fellowships (HonFRPS)|publisher=[[Royal Photographic Society]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127135803/http://www.rps.org/about/awards/history-and-recipients/honorary-fellowships|archive-date=27 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> \n* 2013 Minister of Education Award for New Artists\n* 2013 Higashikawa Domestic Photographer Award\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Hanako.'' 2002.\n* ''Utatane.'' 2002.\n* ''Hanabi'' ({{Nihongo2|\u82b1\u706b}}, Fireworks). Tokyo: Little More, 2002. {{ISBN|4-89815-053-5}}.\n* ''Aila.'' 2004.\n* ''The eyes, the ears.'' 2005.\n* ''Cui Cui.'' 2005.\n* ''Semear.'' 2007.\n* ''Murmuration.'' Brighton: [[Photoworks]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-1-903796-41-2}}.\n* ''One Day - 10 Photographers,'' Heidelberg/Berlin: Kehrer, 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-86828-173-6}}, edited by Harvey Benge.<ref group=\"n\">The publisher's description of this set: {{Cite web|url=https://www.kehrerverlag.com/en/one-day-10-photographers-978-3-86828-173-6|title=One Day - Kehrer Verlag|website=Kehrer Verlag|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n* ''Illuminance.'' New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2011. {{ISBN|978-1597111447}}.\n* ''Approaching Whiteness.'' Tokyo: Goliga, 2012.\n* ''Ametsuchi.'' New York: Aperture, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1597112161}}.\n* ''Light and Shadow''. Kanagawa, Japan : Super Labo,  2014<ref>{{Cite book|title=Light and shadow|last=Kawauchi|first=Rinko|date=2014|isbn=9784905052678|oclc = 907485744}}</ref>\n* ''Halo.'' New York: Aperture, 2017. {{ISBN|1597114111}}.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n=== Solo exhibitions ===\n*1998: ''Utatane'', Guardian Garden, Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapispress.com/rinkokawauchi_detail.htm|title=The Lapis Press|website=www.lapispress.com}}</ref>\n*2006: ''Rinko Kawauchi,'' [[The Photographers' Gallery]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonEvents/RinkoKawauchi/c1b89|title=London Town|publisher=}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.photonet.org.uk/index.php?id=130,578,0,0,1,0 Rinko Kawauchi, 5 May - 9 July 2006, The Photographers' Gallery]\"</ref>\n*2007: ''Semear,'' [[Museu de Arte Moderna de S\u00e3o Paulo]], S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>Rinko Kawauchi, Museu de Arte Moderna de S\u00e3o Paulo, S\u00e3o Paulo 20 jul-23 set 2007 {{cite web |url=http://www.mam.org.br/2008/portugues/exposicaoDetalhes.aspx?id=31 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007230855/http://www.mam.org.br/2008/portugues/exposicaoDetalhes.aspx?id=31 |archivedate=2010-10-07 }}</ref>\